node.text: This video is a great example of how narrative format can be used to get and keep people's attention. It can be highly effective by any creator on any platform. This British Airways commercial has 7.4 million views online using a narrative "short film" format that captures your emotional investment and keeps you engaged for the STORY instead of the product. It makes you want to watch until the end and leaves you with a lasting good feeling. Once that's achieved, all the company needs to do is add their logo or slogan for you to make the connection to the brand. The next time you think about how the story has moved you, you automatically remember the company or product associated with it.

node.text:
While most people may not be able to relate to being deaf-mute, most can relate to feeling unheard or misunderstood for our good intentions. We created this piece to encourage everyone to give the benefit of the doubt to those around us. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣
We wanted to produce a piece that creates an emotional build up in the viewer - like a film.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
But in order to make this piece stand out in the fast social media space, we condensed the storyline and aimed to hit the key points hard and fast. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Here's a quick formula breakdown of how we designed it:⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣
• Open the story with a situation that would immediately form the viewer's opinion or empathy for a character ie. people mistreating the beggar and throwing things at him⁣⁣
• Follow up by another more high strung situation to build on that opinion ie. the misunderstood beggar gets pushed and accidentally bumps into an angry pregnant couple⁣⁣
• Raise the stakes even higher by introducing a third situation that digs a deeper grave for our misunderstood character ie. villain steals the purse and baby while the beggar becomes the scapegoat ⁣⁣
• Resolve the issue with a twist, subverting the viewers' expectations ie. couple gets their baby back from whom they originally accused as the cause of their trouble⁣⁣
• End with justice ie. we see the beggar is now being rewarded for his good deed and the couple finally sees him in a good light⁣⁣
⁣⁣

node.text:
I asked musicians to compose a song for your ❤️ and this is what happened....

I personally shot this video of my friends @bog_vln & @matidavia while working on their latest project: @alchemy.breath.sound   In working with them I wanted to create a Hook Point that could bring people into their powerful style of music.  @adambombr1 built this unique heart that can light up and match the beat of music.  So after a few hours of brainstorming I came up with the Hook Point: “A concert for your heart.”  This video serves as the first test of this series.  

There were a few reasons I went with this direction:

1. To stop the scroll (the first signal to algorithms that this is a quality piece of content), I needed to find a way to interrupt the pattern of other content people are typically consuming in their feed.  The heart flashing different colors as the musicians play does just that.  

2. The meme card “Musicians compose a song for your ❤️” is designed to speak directly to the single person watching the video.  One of the biggest mistakes people make with social media is thinking that it is a one too many platform, when in reality it is a one-to-one communication tool.  The “for YOUR ❤️” signals subconsciously that this video was created just for them.  

3. I wanted to show the song being created on the spot.  We have recently seen a few musicians grow extremely fast on social media while showing the actual creation process.  The reason for this is that it builds retention—one of the most important things needed to get reach from the algorithms—because people want to see what is going to happen next and what the final product will turn out to be.  There were several other videos I shot and edited that didn’t show the creation process and although the music was extremely beautiful it came off as passive experience and not an active one.  

What do you feel about this video?
